Scoring Dashboard: Model Evaluation & Drift Analysis

Purpose: Evaluate trained models on point-in-time holdout data and analyze distribution drift.

What you'll learn:

  • How models perform on truly unseen data (not random holdout)
  • Distribution drift between training and scoring populations
  • Side-by-side comparison of validation vs scoring metrics
  • Actionable recommendations based on drift analysis

def get_latest_snapshot():
    snapshots = sorted(SNAPSHOT_DIR.glob("training_v*.parquet"), key=lambda p: p.stat().st_mtime, reverse=True)
    return pd.read_parquet(snapshots[0]), snapshots[0].name

# Load models directly from model registry artifacts
import os
import pickle
import yaml

print(f"Current working directory: {os.getcwd()}")
print(f"MLflow tracking URI: {MLFLOW_TRACKING_URI}")
print(f"URI exists: {Path(MLFLOW_TRACKING_URI).exists()}")

client = mlflow.tracking.MlflowClient()
experiment = client.get_experiment_by_name(PIPELINE_NAME)

if experiment is None:
    raise RuntimeError(f"Experiment '{PIPELINE_NAME}' not found!")
    
print(f"Experiment found: {experiment.name} (ID: {experiment.experiment_id})")

# Find models with actual artifacts in the models directory
models_dir = Path(MLFLOW_TRACKING_URI) / experiment.experiment_id / "models"
MODEL_TYPES = ["logistic_regression", "random_forest", "xgboost"]
models = {}

# Find the latest model with artifacts for each type
for model_type in MODEL_TYPES:
    best_model_dir = None
    best_timestamp = 0
    
    for model_dir in models_dir.glob("m-*"):
        meta_file = model_dir / "meta.yaml"
        artifacts_dir = model_dir / "artifacts"
        model_file = artifacts_dir / "model.pkl"
        
        if meta_file.exists() and model_file.exists():
            with open(meta_file) as f:
                meta = yaml.safe_load(f)
            
            if model_type in meta.get("name", ""):
                timestamp = meta.get("creation_timestamp", 0)
                if timestamp > best_timestamp:
                    best_timestamp = timestamp
                    best_model_dir = model_dir
    
    if best_model_dir:
        model_file = best_model_dir / "artifacts" / "model.pkl"
        with open(model_file, "rb") as f:
            model = pickle.load(f)
        
        # Get metrics from the source run
        meta_file = best_model_dir / "meta.yaml"
        with open(meta_file) as f:
            meta = yaml.safe_load(f)
        source_run_id = meta.get("source_run_id", "")
        
        try:
            run = client.get_run(source_run_id)
            metrics = run.data.metrics
        except:
            metrics = {}
        
        models[model_type] = {
            "model": model,
            "run_id": source_run_id,
            "metrics": metrics,
            "model_name": meta.get("name", "")
        }
        print(f"  Loaded {model_type} from {meta.get('name', 'unknown')}")
    else:
        print(f"  No artifacts found for {model_type}")

print(f"\nLoaded {len(models)} models")

if not models:
    print("\nWARNING: No models could be loaded!")
    print("You may need to re-run the training pipeline to generate model artifacts.")

4. Prepare Features for Scoring

In[4]:
Show/Hide Code 
def get_model_feature_names(model):
    """Get feature names from trained model."""
    if hasattr(model, 'feature_names_in_'):
        return list(model.feature_names_in_)
    elif hasattr(model, 'feature_name_'):
        return model.feature_name_()
    elif hasattr(model, 'get_booster'):
        return model.get_booster().feature_names
    return None

def prepare_features_for_model(df, model):
    """Prepare features aligned with model's expected feature order."""
    feature_names = get_model_feature_names(model)
    
    if feature_names is None:
        raise ValueError("Could not determine feature names from model")
    
    result = pd.DataFrame(index=df.index)
    
    for col in feature_names:
        if col in df.columns:
            if df[col].dtype == 'object' or df[col].dtype.name == 'category':
                result[col] = LabelEncoder().fit_transform(df[col].astype(str))
            else:
                result[col] = df[col].fillna(0)
        else:
            result[col] = 0
    
    return result[feature_names]

5. Evaluate All Models on Scoring Data

In[5]:
Show/Hide Code 
from sklearn.dummy import DummyClassifier

def evaluate_model(model, X, y_true):
    """Evaluate model with aligned features."""
    y_proba = model.predict_proba(X)[:, 1] if hasattr(model, 'predict_proba') else model.predict(X)
    y_pred = (y_proba >= 0.5).astype(int)
    return {
        "y_pred": y_pred,
        "y_proba": y_proba,
        "roc_auc": roc_auc_score(y_true, y_proba),
        "pr_auc": average_precision_score(y_true, y_proba),
        "f1": f1_score(y_true, y_pred),
        "precision": precision_score(y_true, y_pred),
        "recall": recall_score(y_true, y_pred),
        "accuracy": accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)
    }

y_scoring = scoring_df["actual"].values
scoring_results = {}

# Evaluate trained models
for name, data in models.items():
    model = data["model"]
    X_scoring = prepare_features_for_model(scoring_df, model)
    scoring_results[name] = evaluate_model(model, X_scoring, y_scoring)
    print(f"{name}: ROC-AUC={scoring_results[name]['roc_auc']:.4f}, F1={scoring_results[name]['f1']:.4f}")

# Add Naive (Dummy) Classifier as baseline
# Uses actual class distribution - predicts P(retained) = observed retention rate
# This represents a "no-skill" model that only knows the class proportions
X_scoring_first = prepare_features_for_model(scoring_df, first_model)
retention_rate = y_scoring.mean()  # Actual proportion of retained customers
print(f"\nActual class distribution: {retention_rate:.1%} retained, {1-retention_rate:.1%} churned")

# Create dummy classifier that uses prior probabilities (class distribution)
dummy_clf = DummyClassifier(strategy='prior', random_state=42)
dummy_clf.fit(X_scoring_first, y_scoring)
scoring_results["naive_baseline"] = evaluate_model(dummy_clf, X_scoring_first, y_scoring)
print(f"naive_baseline: ROC-AUC={scoring_results['naive_baseline']['roc_auc']:.4f}, F1={scoring_results['naive_baseline']['f1']:.4f}")
print(f"  (Predicts {retention_rate:.1%} probability for all samples)")

        val_metrics = models[model_type]["metrics"]
        score_metrics = scoring_results[model_type]
        comparison_data.append({
            "Model": model_type.replace("_", " ").title(),

            "Val F1": val_metrics.get("f1", 0),
            "Score F1": score_metrics["f1"],
            "F1 Gap": val_metrics.get("f1", 0) - score_metrics["f1"],
            "Val Precision": val_metrics.get("precision", 0),
            "Score Precision": score_metrics["precision"],
            "Val Recall": val_metrics.get("recall", 0),

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(16, 5))

model_names = [d["Model"] for d in comparison_data]
x = np.arange(len(model_names))
width = 0.35

metrics_to_plot = [("Val ROC-AUC", "Score ROC-AUC", "ROC-AUC"),
                   ("Val F1", "Score F1", "F1 Score"),
                   ("Val Precision", "Score Precision", "Precision")]

# Colors: trained models in blue/coral, naive baseline in gray
n_trained = len(MODEL_TYPES_DISPLAY)
bar_colors_val = ['steelblue'] * n_trained + ['gray']
bar_colors_score = ['coral'] * n_trained + ['darkgray']

for ax, (val_col, score_col, title) in zip(axes, metrics_to_plot):
    val_vals = [d[val_col] if not pd.isna(d[val_col]) else 0 for d in comparison_data]
    score_vals = [d[score_col] if not pd.isna(d[score_col]) else 0 for d in comparison_data]
    
    # Plot bars with different colors for baseline
    for i, (v_val, s_val) in enumerate(zip(val_vals, score_vals)):
        # Skip if model not available (NaN)
        if pd.isna(comparison_data[i].get("Score ROC-AUC")) and i < n_trained:
            ax.bar(x[i] - width/2, 0, width, color='lightgray', edgecolor='white', hatch='//')
            ax.bar(x[i] + width/2, 0, width, color='lightgray', edgecolor='white', hatch='//')
            ax.text(x[i], 0.05, 'N/A', ha='center', fontsize=9, color='gray')
        else:
            ax.bar(x[i] - width/2, v_val, width, color=bar_colors_val[i], 
                   label='Validation' if i == 0 else '', edgecolor='white')
            ax.bar(x[i] + width/2, s_val, width, color=bar_colors_score[i],
                   label='Scoring' if i == 0 else '', edgecolor='white')
    
    ax.set_ylabel(title)
    ax.set_xticks(x)
    # Shorter labels for x-axis
    short_names = []
    for name in model_names:
        if "Naive" in name:
            short_names.append("Naive")
        else:
            short_names.append(name.split()[0])
    ax.set_xticklabels(short_names, rotation=15)
    ax.legend()
    ax.set_ylim(0, 1.0)
    ax.set_title(f"{title} Comparison")
    
    # Add horizontal line at 0.5 for ROC-AUC (random baseline reference)
    if title == "ROC-AUC":
        ax.axhline(y=0.5, color='red', linestyle=':', alpha=0.7)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.suptitle("Validation vs Scoring Performance (with Naive Baseline)", y=1.02, fontsize=14)

8. Distribution Drift Analysis

Compare feature distributions between training snapshot and scoring holdout.

In[9]:
Show/Hide Code 
# Get numeric features that exist in both training and scoring data
NUMERIC_FEATURES = ['esent', 'eopenrate', 'eclickrate', 'avgorder', 'ordfreq']
available_numeric = [f for f in NUMERIC_FEATURES if f in training_df.columns and f in scoring_df.columns]

drift_data = []
for col in available_numeric:
    train_mean, train_std = training_df[col].mean(), training_df[col].std()
    score_mean, score_std = scoring_df[col].mean(), scoring_df[col].std()
    drift_pct = (score_mean - train_mean) / train_mean * 100 if train_mean != 0 else 0
    z_score = abs(score_mean - train_mean) / train_std if train_std > 0 else 0
    drift_data.append({
        "Feature": col,
        "Train Mean": train_mean,
        "Train Std": train_std,
        "Score Mean": score_mean,
        "Score Std": score_std,
        "Drift %": drift_pct,
        "Z-Score": z_score,
        "Significant": " YES" if (abs(drift_pct) > 20 or z_score > 2) else "No"
    })

target_col = 'target' if 'target' in training_df.columns else TARGET_COLUMN
train_retention = training_df[target_col].mean()
score_retention = scoring_df['actual'].mean()
drift_data.append({
    "Feature": "TARGET (retention)",
    "Train Mean": train_retention,
    "Train Std": 0,
    "Score Mean": score_retention,
    "Score Std": 0,
    "Drift %": (score_retention - train_retention) / train_retention * 100,
    "Z-Score": 0,
    "Significant": " YES" if abs(score_retention - train_retention) > 0.05 else "No"
})

drift_df = pd.DataFrame(drift_data).round(3)
print("=" * 90)
print("DISTRIBUTION DRIFT ANALYSIS: TRAINING vs SCORING")
print("=" * 90)
display(drift_df)

    ax = axes[i]
    ax.hist(training_df[col].dropna(), bins=30, alpha=0.5, label='Training', color='steelblue', density=True)
    ax.hist(scoring_df[col].dropna(), bins=30, alpha=0.5, label='Scoring', color='coral', density=True)
    ax.axvline(training_df[col].mean(), color='steelblue', linestyle='--', lw=2)
    ax.axvline(scoring_df[col].mean(), color='coral', linestyle='--', lw=2)
    drift_info = next((d for d in drift_data if d["Feature"] == col), None)
    title = f"{col}\nDrift: {drift_info['Drift %']:+.1f}%" if drift_info else col
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=11)
    ax.legend()

# Target distribution
ax = axes[len(available_numeric)]
categories = ['Training', 'Scoring']
retained = [train_retention * 100, score_retention * 100]
churned = [(1-train_retention) * 100, (1-score_retention) * 100]
ax.bar(categories, retained, label='Retained', color='forestgreen')
ax.bar(categories, churned, bottom=retained, label='Churned', color='crimson')
ax.set_ylabel('Percentage')
ax.set_title(f"Target Distribution\nTrain: {train_retention:.1%} vs Score: {score_retention:.1%}")
ax.legend()

# Hide empty axes
for j in range(len(available_numeric) + 1, len(axes)):
    axes[j].set_visible(False)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.suptitle("Feature Distribution Comparison: Training vs Scoring", y=1.02, fontsize=14)
plt.show()

11. Feature Importance Comparison

def get_feature_importance(model, feature_names):
    """Extract feature importance from model."""
    if hasattr(model, 'feature_importances_'):
        return pd.DataFrame({
            'feature': feature_names,
            'importance': model.feature_importances_
        }).sort_values('importance', ascending=False)
    elif hasattr(model, 'coef_'):
        return pd.DataFrame({
            'feature': feature_names,
            'importance': np.abs(model.coef_[0])
        }).sort_values('importance', ascending=False)
    return None

# Get feature importance for each model

for i, (name, data) in enumerate(models.items()):
    model = data["model"]
    model_features = get_model_feature_names(model)
    fi = get_feature_importance(model, model_features)
    
    if fi is not None:
        ax = axes[i] if len(models) > 1 else axes
        colors = plt.cm.Blues(np.linspace(0.4, 0.8, len(fi)))
        ax.barh(fi['feature'], fi['importance'], color=colors[::-1])
        ax.set_xlabel('Importance')
        ax.set_title(f"{name.replace('_', ' ').title()}\nFeature Importance")
        ax.invert_yaxis()

import shap

# Use best model for SHAP analysis (typically XGBoost or Random Forest)
best_model_name = best_model[0]
best_model_obj = models[best_model_name]["model"]

print(f"Creating SHAP explainer for {best_model_name}...")

# Prepare features for SHAP
X_shap = prepare_features_for_model(scoring_df, best_model_obj)

# Sample for faster computation if dataset is large
sample_size = min(500, len(X_shap))
X_sample = X_shap.sample(n=sample_size, random_state=42)

# Create appropriate explainer based on model type
if best_model_name == "xgboost":
    explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(best_model_obj)
elif best_model_name == "random_forest":
    explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(best_model_obj)
else:  # logistic_regression
    explainer = shap.LinearExplainer(best_model_obj, X_sample)

shap_values = explainer.shap_values(X_sample)

# Handle different SHAP value formats
if isinstance(shap_values, list):
    # For binary classification, use positive class
    shap_values = shap_values[1]

print(f"SHAP values computed for {sample_size} samples")

Individual Prediction Explanations

Waterfall plots showing how features contribute to specific predictions.

In[17]:
Show/Hide Code 
# Show waterfall plots for a few example predictions
# Find indices for: high confidence retained, high confidence churned, borderline case
y_proba_sample = best_model_obj.predict_proba(X_sample)[:, 1]

high_retain_idx = np.argmax(y_proba_sample)  # Most likely to be retained
high_churn_idx = np.argmin(y_proba_sample)   # Most likely to churn
borderline_idx = np.argmin(np.abs(y_proba_sample - 0.5))  # Closest to 0.5

examples = [
    ("High Confidence RETAINED", high_retain_idx, y_proba_sample[high_retain_idx]),
    ("High Confidence CHURNED", high_churn_idx, y_proba_sample[high_churn_idx]),
    ("Borderline Case", borderline_idx, y_proba_sample[borderline_idx])
]

# Get base value for SHAP explanations
if hasattr(explainer, 'expected_value'):
    if isinstance(explainer.expected_value, (list, np.ndarray)):
        base_value = explainer.expected_value[1] if len(explainer.expected_value) > 1 else explainer.expected_value[0]
    else:
        base_value = explainer.expected_value
else:
    base_value = 0

# Create separate waterfall plot for each example
for title, idx, prob in examples:
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))

    explanation = shap.Explanation(
        values=shap_values[idx],
        base_values=base_value,
        data=X_sample.iloc[idx].values,
        feature_names=list(X_sample.columns)
    )

    shap.waterfall_plot(explanation, show=False, max_display=10)
    plt.title(f"SHAP Waterfall: {title}\nP(Retained) = {prob:.2%}", fontsize=14)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

from sklearn.inspection import PartialDependenceDisplay

# Create Partial Dependence Plots for top 4 features
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

# Get feature indices for top features
feature_indices = [list(X_sample.columns).index(f) for f in top_features]

PartialDependenceDisplay.from_estimator(
    best_model_obj,
    X_sample,
    features=feature_indices,
    feature_names=list(X_sample.columns),
    ax=axes.flatten(),
    kind='both',  # Shows both individual (ICE) lines and average (PDP)
    subsample=100,
    random_state=42,
    ice_lines_kw={'color': 'lightblue', 'alpha': 0.3, 'linewidth': 0.5},
    pd_line_kw={'color': 'darkblue', 'linewidth': 2}
)

for ax, feature in zip(axes.flatten(), top_features):
    ax.set_title(f"Partial Dependence: {feature}", fontsize=11)
